**Sec. 10101. Re-evaluation of thrifty food plan.**
The Secretary of Agriculture must base SNAP allotments on the 2021 Thrifty Food Plan cost for a standard family of four, applying fixed percentage ratios for households of different sizes (e.g., 30% for one person, 100% for four). Cost adjustments for Hawaii, Alaska, Guam, and the Virgin Islands are permitted to reflect local food prices, with annual inflation adjustments tied to the Consumer Price Index starting October 1, 2025. Market basket re-evaluations may occur no earlier than October 1, 2027, but any changes must be cost-neutral and cannot increase the overall plan cost.

**Sec. 10102. Modifications to SNAP work requirements for able-bodied adults.**
The bill expands exemptions from SNAP work requirements for able-bodied adults to include pregnant women, California Indians, and individuals over 65 or under 18. It defines "noncontiguous States" as those outside the contiguous 48 states and D.C., excluding Guam and the Virgin Islands, and allows the Secretary to exempt states from work requirements if they demonstrate a good faith effort to comply. Such exemptions are valid until December 31, 2028, and require quarterly progress reports from state agencies regarding barriers and compliance milestones.

**Sec. 10103. Availability of standard utility allowances based on receipt of energy assistance.**
The bill amends SNAP rules to allow households with an elderly or disabled member to receive standard utility allowances based on energy assistance receipt, while households without such members must meet different criteria. Specifically, third-party energy assistance payments are now treated differently depending on whether the household includes an elderly or disabled member, altering how these payments are counted against utility allowances.

**Sec. 10104. Restrictions on internet expenses.**
The bill explicitly prohibits the use of any service fees associated with internet connections when calculating the excess shelter expense deduction for SNAP households. This change ensures that internet costs cannot be factored into the shelter expense limits used to determine benefit amounts.

**Sec. 10105. Matching funds requirements.**
Beginning in fiscal year 2028, the bill ties the federal share of SNAP allotment costs to a state's payment error rate, reducing the federal share from 100% to 85% as error rates rise from below 6% to 10% or higher. States with error rates multiplied by 1.5 exceeding 20% in fiscal years 2025 or 2026 will have their implementation of these new cost-sharing rules delayed until fiscal years 2029 or 2030, respectively. The Secretary is prohibited from paying more than the applicable federal share determined by these new tiers.

**Sec. 10106. Administrative cost sharing.**
The bill reduces the federal share of administrative costs for SNAP state agencies from 50% to 25% for fiscal year 2027 and all subsequent fiscal years, down from the previous 50% rate that applied through fiscal year 2026. This change shifts a larger portion of administrative financial responsibility onto the states.

**Sec. 10107. National education and obesity prevention grant program.**
The bill extends the authorization for the National Education and Obesity Prevention Grant Program to cover fiscal years 2016 through 2025, whereas previous provisions may have had different expiration dates. This ensures continued funding for the program through the end of the 2025 fiscal year.

**Sec. 10108. Alien SNAP eligibility.**
The bill restricts SNAP eligibility to U.S. citizens, nationals, lawful permanent residents, Cuban and Haitian entrants, and individuals under Compact of Free Association agreements, effectively excluding temporary visitors, tourists, diplomats, and students. The income and financial resources of any household member rendered ineligible under these new restrictions must still be counted when determining the eligibility and allotment value for the rest of the household.

**Sec. 10201. Rescission of amounts for forestry.**
The bill rescinds all unobligated balances from specific provisions of Public Law 117-169 related to forestry, including sections 23001(a)(3)-(4), 23002(a)(1)-(4), 23003(a)(2), and 23005. This action removes these funds from the Treasury without further obligation.

**Sec. 10301. Effective reference price; reference price.**
The bill increases the effective reference price for Price Loss Coverage (PLC) from 85% to 88% of the reference price starting with the 2025 crop year. It establishes new fixed reference prices for covered commodities for the 2025 crop year, such as $6.35 per bushel for wheat and $10.00 per bushel for soybeans, with automatic 0.5% annual increases starting in 2031 capped at 113% of the 2025 levels.

**Sec. 10302. Base acres.**
The bill authorizes the Secretary to allocate up to 30,000,000 additional base acres to eligible farms starting with the 2026 crop year, based on a comparison of 5-year average planted acreage (2019-2023) against existing base acres. Eligibility requires that the 5-year average of planted and prevented planting acreage for covered and eligible noncovered commodities exceeds the current base acres, with specific formulas for allocation among commodities. If the total eligible acres exceed 30 million, the Secretary must apply an across-the-board pro-rata reduction to meet the cap.

**Sec. 10303. Producer election.**
The bill extends the deadline for producers to elect coverage programs from 2023 to 2031 and allows elections for the 2026 crop year. It mandates that for the 2025 crop year, producers receive the higher of Price Loss Coverage or Agriculture Risk Coverage payments on a commodity-by-commodity basis. Additionally, it updates the definition of acres eligible for the Supplemental Coverage Option to include all acres regardless of the producer's PLC or ARC election.

**Sec. 10304. Price loss coverage.**
The bill extends the availability of Price Loss Coverage (PLC) payments through the 2031 crop year and updates the reference price calculation to use the 2017 through 2021 crop years instead of 2012 through 2016. It also corrects statutory references to ensure the correct reference price definitions are applied for rice commodities.

**Sec. 10305. Agriculture risk coverage.**
The bill extends Agriculture Risk Coverage (ARC) coverage through the 2031 crop year and adjusts the benchmark revenue calculation to use 90% of the benchmark revenue for the 2025 through 2031 crop years. It increases the trigger threshold for ARC payments from 10% to 12% of benchmark revenue for the 2025 through 2031 crop years, while maintaining the 10% threshold for 2014 through 2024.

**Sec. 10306. Equitable treatment of certain entities.**
The bill redefines "qualified pass-through entity" to include partnerships, S corporations, LLCs not electing corporate status, and joint ventures, replacing previous exclusions for joint ventures and general partnerships in payment limitation and attribution rules. This change ensures these specific business structures are treated consistently across various agricultural program provisions, including those related to actively engaged in farming and joint and several liability.

**Sec. 10307. Payment limitations.**
The bill increases the payment limitation for most farm programs from $125,000 to $155,000 per person or legal entity for the 2025 crop year and subsequent years. It also mandates that these limits be adjusted annually for inflation based on the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers.

**Sec. 10308. Adjusted gross income limitation.**
The bill adds an exception to the Adjusted Gross Income (AGI) limitation, allowing individuals or entities to exceed the limit if at least 75% of their average gross income derives from farming, ranching, or silviculture activities. This exception applies to payments from specific programs like PLC, ARC, and certain disaster assistance, ensuring that active agricultural operators are not disqualified based on non-farm income.

**Sec. 10309. Marketing loans.**
The bill extends the availability of nonrecourse marketing assistance loans through the 2031 crop year and establishes new loan rates for 2026 through 2031, such as $2.42 per bushel for corn and $6.82 per bushel for soybeans. It also introduces cotton storage payments for the 2026 through 2031 crop years, with rates of $4.90 per hundredweight in California and Arizona and $3.00 elsewhere.

**Sec. 10310. Repayment of marketing loans.**
The bill modifies marketing loan repayment rules to allow repayment at the prevailing world market price for rice and upland cotton, with a refund mechanism for cotton producers if the world price drops after repayment. It also updates the formula for determining the prevailing world market price for extra long staple cotton to include adjustments for quality, location, and transportation costs, with provisions to minimize loan forfeitures.

**Sec. 10311. Economic adjustment assistance for textile mills.**
The bill increases the value of economic adjustment assistance for textile mills from 3 cents per pound to 5 cents per pound for the period beginning August 1, 2025. This assistance applies to cotton used in textile production and is intended to support mills facing economic challenges.

**Sec. 10312. Sugar program updates.**
The bill sets the sugar loan rate at 24.00 cents per pound for raw cane sugar and establishes a corresponding rate for refined sugar for the 2025 through 2031 crop years. It increases Commodity Credit Corporation storage rates for forfeited sugar to 34 cents per hundredweight per month for refined sugar and 27 cents for raw cane sugar. Additionally, it mandates a study on refined sugar import terms and allows for reallocation of tariff-rate quota shortfalls.

**Sec. 10313. Dairy policy updates.**
The bill increases the Dairy Margin Coverage (DMC) production history limit from 5,000,000 pounds to 6,000,000 pounds for both Tier I and Tier II coverage. It extends the duration of the DMC program through the 2031 crop year and updates premium discounts to apply to the 2026 through 2031 period.

**Sec. 10314. Implementation.**
The bill allocates $50,000,000 for the implementation of the commodity subtitle, with specific amounts designated for dairy production cost surveys ($9,000,000), the refined sugar study ($1,000,000), and other administrative activities. These funds are to remain available until expended to support the new provisions enacted in the commodity subtitle.

**Sec. 10401. Supplemental agricultural disaster assistance.**
The bill increases Livestock Indemnity Program (LIP) payment rates to 100% of market value for predation losses and 75% for adverse weather or disease losses, while adding payments for unborn livestock deaths at up to 85% of the lowest weight class rate. It expands the Livestock Forage Disaster Program to allow payments for 4 consecutive weeks of drought instead of 8, and adds assistance for losses due to bird depredation on farm-raised fish at a minimum of $600 per acre.

**Sec. 10501. Beginning farmer and rancher benefit.**
The bill increases the definition of a "beginning farmer or rancher" from 10 years or less of experience to 10 years or less, effectively expanding the eligibility window. It provides additional premium assistance for beginning farmers, adding 5 percentage points for the first two reinsurance years, 3 points for the third year, and 1 point for the fourth year.

**Sec. 10502. Area-based crop insurance coverage and affordability.**
The bill increases the maximum coverage level for area-based crop insurance plans to 95% and raises the premium subsidy rate for these plans from 65% to 80%. It also adjusts the coverage level aggregation rules to allow up to 90% coverage for individual yield or revenue coverage aggregated across multiple commodities.

**Sec. 10503. Administrative and operating expense adjustments.**
The bill mandates additional administrative and operating expense subsidies for approved insurance providers, including a 6% payment on net book premiums for eligible contracts in high-loss states. It also sets a minimum reimbursement rate of 17% of the premium for specialty crops and adjusts A&O reimbursements for inflation starting in the 2026 reinsurance year.

**Sec. 10504. Premium support.**
The bill increases premium support rates for various coverage levels, raising the base subsidy from 64% to 69% for the highest coverage tier and adjusting other tiers accordingly (e.g., from 59% to 64%, 55% to 60%, etc.). These increases apply to the standard premium support tiers defined in the Federal Crop Insurance Act.

**Sec. 10505. Program compliance and integrity.**
The bill increases the maximum penalty for program violations from $4,000,000 to $6,000,000 for fiscal year 2026 and subsequent years, up from the previous limit of $4,000,000 for fiscal years 2009 through 2025. This change aims to strengthen enforcement and integrity measures within the crop insurance program.

**Sec. 10506. Reviews, compliance, and integrity.**
The bill increases the funding for reviews, compliance, and integrity activities from unspecified amounts to $10,000,000 for fiscal year 2026 and each fiscal year thereafter, up from the previous funding levels for 2014 through 2025. This additional funding supports enhanced oversight and audit capabilities.

**Sec. 10507. Poultry insurance pilot program.**
The bill establishes a pilot program for index-based insurance for contract poultry growers to cover extreme weather-related risks that increase utility costs. The program will be conducted in top poultry-producing states and must be approved by the Board within two years of enactment.

**Sec. 10601. Conservation.**
The bill increases funding for various conservation programs, including the Conservation Stewardship Program, which receives $625,000,000 for fiscal year 2026 and increases to $700,000,000 by 2029. It also allocates $425,000,000 for the Regional Conservation Partnership Program in 2026, rising to $450,000,000 by 2027, and provides $150,000,000 annually for watershed protection starting in 2026.

**Sec. 10602. Supplemental agricultural trade promotion program.**
The bill authorizes $285,000,000 for fiscal year 2027 and each fiscal year thereafter for the Supplemental Agricultural Trade Promotion Program to support the development and expansion of U.S. agricultural export markets. This funding is drawn from the Commodity Credit Corporation.

**Sec. 10603. Nutrition.**
The bill extends the authorization for the Emergency Food Assistance Act nutrition programs through fiscal year 2031, ensuring continued support for food distribution to those in need. This extension maintains the program's funding and operational capacity for the specified period.

**Sec. 10604. Research.**
The bill provides significant new funding for agricultural research, including $37,000,000 for the Foundation for Food and Agriculture Research, $60,000,000 for scholarships at 1890 institutions, and $8,000,000 for assistive technology for farmers with disabilities. It also increases funding for the Specialty Crop Research Initiative to $175,000,000 for fiscal year 2026 and allocates $125,000,000 annually for research facilities starting in 2026.

**Sec. 10605. Energy.**
The bill extends the authorization for the Biomass Crop Assistance Program and other energy-related agricultural programs through fiscal year 2031. This ensures continued support for renewable energy production from agricultural sources.

**Sec. 10606. Horticulture.**
The bill increases funding for plant pest and disease management to $90,000,000 for fiscal year 2026 and raises specialty crop block grants to $100,000,000 for the same year. It also allocates $10,000,000 for the Organic Production and Market Data Initiative for fiscal years 2026 through 2031 and $5,000,000 for a multiple crop and pesticide use survey in 2026.

**Sec. 10607. Miscellaneous.**
The bill allocates $233,000,000 annually for fiscal years 2026 through 2030 for animal disease prevention and management, with specific amounts designated for different subsections. It also provides $3,000,000 for the Sheep Production and Marketing Grant Program in 2026 and extends the authorization for various trust funds, including the Pima Agriculture Cotton Trust Fund and the Wool Research and Promotion program, through 2031. [end of text]


